<section xml:id="section-2A-equations-and-absolute-value">
  <title>Equations and Absolute Value</title>
  <introduction>
    <ul>
      <li>Solve equations (including equations with variables on both sides) by balancing and using inverse operations.</li>
      <li>Solve linear absolute value equations.</li>
      <li>Solve linear distance equation problems.</li>
    </ul>
  </introduction>
  <subsection>
    <title>Solution to an Equation</title>
    <p>Solving linear equations is an important and fundamental skill in algebra. In algebra, we are often presented with a problem where the answer is known, but part of the problem is missing. The missing part of the problem is what we seek to find. An example of such a problem is shown below.</p>
    <example xml:id="example-equation">
      <title>Example Linear Equation</title>
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>LHS \amp = RHS</mrow>
          <mrow>4x+16\amp =-4</mrow>
        </md>
      Equations are of the form "left-hand side" equals "right-hand side" or <term>LHS</term><m>=</m><term>RHS</term> for short<m>.\checkmark</m>
      </p>
    </example>
    <p>Notice the above equation in <xref ref="example-equation" autoname="yes" /> has a missing part, or unknown number, that is marked by
      <m>x.</m> If we are given that the solution to this equation is
      <m>-5</m>, it could be plugged into the equation, replacing the
      <m>x</m> with
      <m>-5.</m> This is shown in
      <xref ref="demonstrate-solution" autoname="yes" />.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="demonstrate-solution">
      <title>A Solution</title>
      <p>Start with the equation
        <m>4x + 16= -4.</m></p>
      <p>
        Let
        <m>x=-5</m> in the <term>LHS</term>:
      </p>
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>4x + 16\amp = -4\amp\amp\text{Substitute \(-5\) for \(x\) in the LHS}</mrow>
          <mrow>4(-5) + 16\amp\amp\amp\text{Multiply \(4(-5)\)}</mrow>
          <mrow>-20+ 16 \amp\amp\amp \text{Add \(-20+ 16\)}</mrow>
          <mrow>-4 \amp\amp\amp \text{Compare the LHS to the RHS}</mrow>
          <mrow>-4\amp = -4\amp\amp \text{LHS=RHS}</mrow>
        </md>
      Since we get a true statement <m>-4=-4</m>, <m>x=-5</m> IS a solution of the equation <m>4x + 16= -4.</m><m>\checkmark</m>
      </p>
    </example>
    <p>Now the equation comes out to a true statement! Notice also that if another number, for example,
      <m>3</m>, were plugged in for
      <m>x</m>, we would not get a true statement as seen in 
      <xref ref="not-a-solution" autoname="yes" />.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="not-a-solution">
      <title>NOT a Solution</title>
      <p>Start with the equation
        <m>4x + 16= -4.</m></p>
        <p>Let
        <m>x=3</m> in the <term>LHS</term>:
      </p>
      <p>
      <md>
        <mrow>4x + 16\amp =-4\amp\amp\text{Substitute \(3\) for \(x\) in the LHS}</mrow>
        <mrow>4(3) + 16 \amp\amp\amp \text{Multiply
        \(4(3)\)}</mrow>
        <mrow>12+ 16 \amp\amp\amp \text{Add
        \(12+ 16\)}</mrow>
        <mrow>28 \amp\amp\amp\text{Compare the LHS to the RHS}</mrow>
        <mrow>28\amp \neq -4 \amp\amp \text{LHS}\neq\text{RHS}</mrow>
      </md>
    Since <m>28\neq -4</m>, <m>x=3</m> is NOT a solution of the equation <m>4x + 16= -4.</m><m>\checkmark</m>
    </p>
    </example>
    <p>Due to the fact that <m>LHS\neq RHS</m>, this demonstrates that
      <m>3</m> is not the solution. However, depending on the complexity of the problem, this "guess and check" method is not very efficient. Thus, we take a more algebraic approach to solving equations. First we will focus on what are called "one-step equations" or equations that only require one step to solve. While these equations often seem very fundamental, it is important to master the pattern for solving these problems so we can solve more complex problems.
    </p>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Linear Equations - One-Step Equations</title>
    <p>To solve equations, we perform mathematical operations to both sides of the equation to isolate the variable.  For example, consider the following:</p>
    <example>
      <title>Solve an Equation Involving Addition</title>
      <p>Solve the equation for <m>x.</m>
      <md>
        <mrow>x+7 \amp = -5 \amp\amp \text{Notice the
        \(7\) is added to the
        \(x\)}</mrow>
        <mrow>(x+7)-7 \amp = (-5) - 7 \amp\amp \text{Subtract
        \(7\) from both sides to isolate
        \(x\)}</mrow>
        <mrow>x \amp = -12 \amp\amp \text{Our Solution}\checkmark</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
    </example>
    
      <assemblage>
        <title>WeBWorK: Entering Solutions to Equations</title>
        <p>Enter the entire expression
          <c>x = -12</c>, NOT just the value
          <c>-12</c>.
        </p>
      </assemblage>
    
    <!--  The same process is used in each of the following examples.
        </p>
        <example>
          <title>Solve Equations Involving Addition</title>
          <md>
            <mrow>4+x=8\amp\amp\amp 7=x+9 \amp\amp\amp 5=8+x</mrow>
            <mrow>\underline{ -4 \,\,\,\,\,\, -4}\amp\amp\amp\underline{-9 \,\,\,\,\,\, -9}\amp\amp\amp\underline{-8\, \, -8 \,\,\,\,\,\,\,}</mrow>
            <mrow>x=4\amp\amp\amp -2=x \amp\amp\amp-3=x</mrow>
          </md>
        </example>
    -->
    <p>The terms in an equation may be in any order and the variable may be a letter 
    other than
      <m>x.</m> The key is to focus on using operations that get 
    the variable by itself on one side of the equals sign.
    </p>
    <example>
      <title>Another Example With Addition</title>
      <p>Solve the equation for <m>t.</m></p>
      <p>In this example,
      <m>5</m> must be subtracted from both sides to solve for
      <m>t.</m>
      <md>
        <mrow>8=5\amp +t</mrow>
        <mrow>\underline{-5\,\,-5}\amp</mrow>
        <mrow>3=t\amp</mrow>
      </md>
      Then we get our solution,
        <m>t = 3.\checkmark</m>
      </p>
    </example>
    <p>In a subtraction problem, we "counteract" negative numbers by adding them to both sides of the equation. For example, consider the following:</p>
    <example>
      <title>Solve an Equation Involving Subtration</title>
      <p>Solve the equation for
        <m>x.</m>
      <md>
        <mrow>x-5\amp = 4 \amp\amp \text{Notice
        \(5\) is  subtracted from
        \(x\)}</mrow>
        <mrow>(x-5)+5\amp = 4+5 \amp\amp \text{Add
        \(5\) to both sides of the equation to solve for
        \(x\)}</mrow>
        <mrow>x\amp = 9 \amp\amp \text{Our Solution}\checkmark</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
    </example>
      <!--The same process is used in each of the following examples. Notice that each time we are "eliminating" a negative number by adding.-->
    
    <!--
        <example>
          <title>Solve Equations Involving Subtraction</title>
          <p></p>
          <md>
            <mrow>-6+x=-2\amp\amp\amp -10=x-7\amp\amp\amp 5=-8+x</mrow>
            <mrow>\underline{ +6 \,\,\,\,\,\, +6}\amp\amp\amp\underline{+7 \,\,\,\,\,\, +7}\amp\amp\amp\underline{-8\, \, -8 \,\,\,\,\,\,\,}</mrow>
            <mrow>x=4\amp\amp\amp -3=x\amp\amp\amp 13=x</mrow>
          </md>
        </example>
    -->
    <p>With a multiplication problem, we "eliminate" a constant multiple by multiplying by the reciprocal (or dividing) on both sides. For example consider the following:</p>
    <example>
      <title>Positive Constant Multiple</title>
      <p>Solve the equation for
        <m>w.</m>
      <md>
        <mrow>4w \amp = 20 \amp\amp \text{Notice the constant multiple
        \(4\) times the variable
        \(w\)}</mrow>
        <mrow>\frac{1}{4}(4w) \amp = \frac{1}{4}\cdot 20 \amp\amp \text{Multiply both sides by
        \(\frac{1}{4}\)(or divide both sides by
        \(4\))}</mrow>
        <mrow>w \amp = 5 \amp\amp \text{Our Solution}\checkmark</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
    </example>
    <p>With multiplication problems it is very important that care is taken with signs. If
      the variable is multiplied by a negative then we will multiply by the negative reciprocal 
      (or divide by a negative.)</p>
    <example>
      <title>Negative Constant Multiple</title>
      <p>Solve the equation for
        <m>x.</m>
      <md>
        <mrow>-5x \amp = 30 \amp\amp \text{
        \(x\) is multiplied by
        \(-5\)}</mrow>
        <mrow>-\frac{1}{5}(-5x) \amp = -\frac{1}{5}\cdot30 \amp\amp \text{Multiply both sides by
        \(-\frac{1}{5}\)}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp\amp\amp\text{(or divide both sides by
        \(-5\))}</mrow>
        <mrow>x\amp =-6 \amp\amp \text{Our Solution}\checkmark</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
    </example>
    <p>The same process is used in each of the following examples. Notice how negative and positive numbers are handled as each problem is solved.</p>
    <example>
      <title>Multiply by Reciprocals</title>
      <p>Solve each equation.</p>
      <sidebyside>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>8t\amp =-24</mrow>
            <mrow>\frac{1}{8}(8t)\amp =(-24)\frac{1}{8}</mrow>
            <mrow>t\amp =-3</mrow>
        </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>-4z\amp =-20</mrow>
            <mrow>\left(-\frac{1}{4}\right)(-4z)\amp =(-20)\left(-\frac{1}{4}\right)</mrow>
            <mrow>z\amp =5</mrow>
        </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>42\amp =7x</mrow>
            <mrow>\frac{1}{7}(42)\amp =\frac{1}{7}(7x)</mrow>
            <mrow>6\amp =x</mrow>
        </md>
        </p>
        </sidebyside>
<!--
      <md>
        <mrow>\amp\amp\amp -4z=-20\amp\amp\amp 42=7x</mrow>
        <mrow>\frac{1}{8}(8t)=(-24)\frac{1}{8}\amp\amp\amp \frac{1}{4}(-4z)=(-20)(-\frac{1}{4}) \amp\amp\amp \frac{1}{7}\cdot 42=\frac{1}{7}(7x)</mrow>
        <mrow>t =-3 \amp\amp\amp z=5 \amp\amp\amp 6=x</mrow>
      </md>-->
    </example>
    <p>In division problems, "eliminate the denominator" by multiplying on both sides. For example consider:</p>
    <example>
      <title>Eliminate Denominator</title>
      <p>Solve the equation for
        <m>t.</m>
      </p>
      <p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\frac{t}{5}\amp =-3 \amp\amp \text{Variable
        \(t\) is divided by
        \(5\)}</mrow>
        <mrow>(5)\frac{t}{5}\amp =-3(5) \amp\amp \text{Multiply both sides by
        \(5\)}</mrow>
        <mrow>t\amp =-15 \amp\amp \text{Our Solution}\checkmark</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
    </example>
    <p>The same process is used in each of the following examples.
    </p>

    <example>
      <title>Eliminate Denominators</title>
      <p>Solve for each variable.</p>
      <sidebyside>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>\frac{x}{-7}\amp =-2</mrow>
            <mrow>(-7)\frac{x}{-7}\amp =-2(-7)</mrow>
            <mrow>x\amp=14</mrow>
        </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>\frac{t}{8}\amp =5</mrow>
            <mrow>(8)\frac{t}{8}\amp =5(8)</mrow>
            <mrow>t\amp =40</mrow>
        </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>\frac{w}{-4}\amp =9</mrow>
            <mrow>(-4)\frac{w}{-4}\amp =9(-4)</mrow>
            <mrow>w\amp =-36</mrow>
        </md>
        </p>
        </sidebyside>
        <!--
      <md>
        <mrow>\frac{x}{-7}=-2 \amp\amp\amp \frac{x}{8}=5 \amp\amp\amp \frac{x}{-4}=9</mrow>
        <mrow>(-7)\frac{x}{-7}=-2(-7) \amp\amp\amp (8)\frac{x}{8}=5(8) \amp\amp\amp (-4)\frac{x}{-4}=9(-4)</mrow>
        <mrow>x=14\amp\amp\amp x=40 \amp\amp\amp x=-36</mrow>
      </md>-->
    </example>
    <p>The process described above is fundamental to solving equations. Once this process is mastered, the problems we will see have several more steps. These problems may seem more complex, but the process and patterns used will remain the same.</p>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Linear Equations - Two-Step Equations</title>
    <p>After mastering the technique for solving equations that are one-step equations, we are ready to consider two-step equations. As we solve two-step equations, the important thing to remember is that everything works backwards! When working with one-step equations, we learned that in order to clear a "plus five" in the equation, we would subtract five from both sides. We learned that to clear "divided by seven" we multiply by seven on both sides. The same pattern applies to the order of operations. When solving for our variable, we use order of operations backwards as well. This means we will add or subtract first, then multiply or divide second (then exponents, and finally any parentheses or grouping symbols, but that's another lesson).</p>
    <example>
      <title>Addition then Division</title>
      <p>Solve the equation for
        <m>.</m>
      </p>
      <p>
      <md>
        <mrow>4x+-20=-8</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
    <p>We have two numbers on the same side as the variable
      <m>x.</m> We need to handle the
      <m>4</m> and the
      <m>-20.</m> We know to "eliminate" the four we need to divide, and to "eliminate" the subtracted twenty we will add twenty to both sides. If order of operations is done backwards, we add or subtract first. Therefore we will add
      <m>20</m> to both sides first. Once we are done with that, we will divide both sides by
      <m>4.</m> The steps are shown below.
    </p>
    <p>
    <md>
      <mrow>4x\color{red}{-20}\color{black}{}\amp= -8 \amp\amp \text{Start by focusing on the subtract
        \(20\)}</mrow>
      <mrow>\underline{+20}\amp\phantom{12}\underline{+20} \amp\amp \text{Add
        \(20\) to both sides}</mrow>
      <mrow>4x\amp = 12 \amp\amp \text{Now we focus on the
        \(4\) multiplied by
        \(x\)}</mrow>
      <mrow>\overline{\,4\,}\amp\phantom{123}\overline{\,4\,} \amp\amp \text{Divide both sides by
        \(4\)}</mrow>
      <mrow>x\amp =3 \amp\amp \text{Our Solution}\checkmark</mrow>
    </md>
  </p>
    <p>One way we can check the correctness of Our Solution is to substitute
      <m>x=3</m> back in to the original equation:
    </p>
    <md>
      <mrow>4x-20 \amp = -8 \amp\amp \text{Substitute
        \(x=3\) into the LHS}
      </mrow>
      <mrow>4(3)-20 \amp\amp\amp \text{Multiply
        \(4(3)\)}</mrow>
      <mrow>12-20 \amp\amp\amp \text{Subtract
        \(12-20\)}</mrow>
      <mrow>-8 \amp\amp\amp\text{Compare the LHS to the RHS}</mrow>
      <mrow>-8\amp =-8\amp\amp\text{LHS=RHS}</mrow>
    </md>
    <p>Since we get a true statement
      <m>-8=-8</m>, Our Solution
      <m>x=3</m> is correct.<m>\checkmark\checkmark</m>
    </p>
  </example>

    <p>The same process is used to solve any two-step equations. Add or subtract first, then multiply or divide. Consider our next example and notice how the same process is applied.</p>
    <example>
      <title>Subtraction then Division</title>
      <p>Solve the equation for
        <m>P.</m>
      </p>
      <p>
      <md>
        <mrow>5P\color{red}{+7}\color{black}{}\amp =7 \amp\amp \text{Start by focusing on the plus
        \(7\)}</mrow>
        <mrow>\underline{-7}\amp\phantom{1}\underline{-7} \amp\amp \text{Subtract
        \(7\) from both sides}</mrow>
        <mrow>5P\amp = 0 \amp\amp \text{Now we focus on the
        \(5\) multiplied by
        \(P\)}</mrow>
        <mrow>\overline{\,5\,}\phantom{1}\amp\phantom{12} \overline{\,5\,} \amp\amp \text{Divide both sides by
        \(5\) (recall
        \(\frac{0}{5}=0\))}</mrow>
        <mrow>P\amp= 0 \amp\amp \text{Our Solution}\checkmark</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
    </example>
    <p>Notice the seven subtracted out completely! Many students get stuck on this point, do not forget that we have a number for "nothing left" and that number is zero. With this in mind the process is almost identical to our first example.</p>
    <p>A common error students make with two-step equations is with negative signs. Remember the sign always stays with the number. Consider the following example.</p>
    <example>
      <title>Negative Coefficient</title>
      <p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\color{red}{4}\color{black}{-2t}\amp = 10 \amp\amp \text{Start by focusing on the positive
      \(4\)}</mrow>
        <mrow>\underline{-4\phantom{1234}}\amp\underline{\phantom{1}-4} \amp\amp \text{Subtract
      \(4\) from both sides}</mrow>
        <mrow>-2t\amp =6 \amp\amp\text{Notice negative
      \(2\) is times
      \(t\) (a negative coefficient)}</mrow>
        <mrow>\overline{-2}\amp\phantom{12}\overline{-2} \amp\amp\text{Divide both sides by
      \(-2\)}</mrow>
        <mrow>t\amp =-3 \amp\amp \text{Our Solution}\checkmark</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
    </example>
    <p>The same is true even if there the coefficient in front of the variable is a negative \(1\). Consider the next example.</p>
    <example>
      <title>Negative Coefficient</title>
      <p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\color{red}{8}\color{black}{-x}\amp =2 \amp\amp\text{Start by focusing on the positive
      \(8\)}</mrow>
        <mrow>\underline{-8\phantom{123}}\amp\underline{\phantom{1}-8}\amp\amp\text{Subtract
      \(8\) from both sides}</mrow>
        <mrow>-x\amp = -6\amp\amp \text{Notice negative
      \(1\) is times
      \(x\)}</mrow>
        <mrow>(-1)(-x)\amp = -6(-1) \amp\amp \text{Multiply both sides by 
      \(-1\)}</mrow>
      <mrow>\amp\amp\amp\text{(or divide both sides by
      \(-1\)) for the same result}</mrow>
        <mrow>x\amp =6 \amp\amp\text{Our Solution}\checkmark</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
    </example>
    <p>Solving two-step equations is a very important skill to master, as we study algebra. The first step is to add or subtract, the second is to multiply or divide. This pattern is seen in each of the following examples.</p>
