      <p>Notice we never combine what is inside the absolute value with what is outside the absolute value. This is very important as it will often change the final result to an incorrect solution. The next example requires two steps to isolate the absolute value. The idea is the same as a two-step equation, add or subtract, then multiply or divide.</p>
      <example>
        <title>Two-Step Absolute Value Equation</title>
        <p>Solve for <m>x.</m>
          <!## Cite Beginning and Intermediate Algebra by Tyler Wallace Example 87 pg 53##>
        </p>
        <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>5\lvert x\rvert -4 = 26 \amp\amp\amp \text{Notice absolute value is not alone on the LHS}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp\amp\amp\text{Isolate the absolute value first}
          </mrow>
          <mrow>\underline{+4\phantom{12}+4} \amp\amp\amp \text{Add
            \(4\) to both sides}</mrow>
          <mrow>5\lvert x\rvert  = 30 \amp\amp\amp \text{Absolute value still not alone}</mrow>
          <mrow>\overline{5\,}\phantom{12345}\overline{\,5\,} \amp\amp\amp \text{Divide both sides by
            \(5\)}</mrow>
          <mrow>\lvert x\rvert  = 6 \amp\amp\amp \text{Absolute value can be positive or negative}</mrow>
          <mrow>\text{
            \(x=6\) or
            \(x=-6\)} \amp\amp\amp \text{Our Solution}\checkmark</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      </example> -->
      <p>Again we see the same process: consider the distance to the left and right of the value. Often the absolute value will have more than just a variable in it. In this case we consider the positive and negative possibilities and solve the resulting equations. This is shown in the next example.</p>
      <example>
        <title>Absolute Value of an Expression</title>
        <p>Solve the equation for <m>x.</m>
          <!-- Cite Beginning and Intermediate Algebra by Tyler Wallace Example 88 pg 53-->
        </p>
        <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>\lvert 2x-1\rvert  = 7 \amp\amp\amp \text{Absolute value can be positive or negative}</mrow>
          <mrow>\text{
            \(2x-1=7\) or
            \(2x-1=-7\)} \amp\amp\amp \text{Two equations to solve}</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
        <p>Now notice we have two equations to solve, each equation will give us a different solution. Both equations solve (separately) like any other two-step equation.</p>
        <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>2x-1=7\amp\amp\amp\text{ OR }\amp\amp\amp 2x-1=-7</mrow>
          <mrow>\underline{+1\,+1}\amp\amp\amp\text{ }\amp\amp\amp\underline{+1\phantom{12}+1}</mrow>
          <mrow>2x=8\amp\amp\amp\text{ }\amp\amp\amp 2x=-6</mrow>
          <mrow>\overline{2}\phantom{1234}\overline{2}\amp\amp\amp\phantom{1234}\amp\amp\amp\overline{2}\phantom{1234}\overline{\,2\,}</mrow>
          <mrow>x=4\amp\amp\amp\text{ OR }\amp\amp\amp x=-3</mrow>
          <mrow>x=4\amp\amp\amp \text{ or }x=-3\amp\amp\amp\text{Our Solution}\checkmark</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      </example>
